deck: Tech-wizard and enemy of Klarion, he is also the head of the Necropolitan Club
description:
Origin

As a young boy, Coal interrupted his father's suicide attempt. His father's shot went astray and merely glanced off his skull, resulting in his survival, while the young Coal was struck by a fragment of his father's skull which burrowed through his chest and into his heart, constantly threatening his life. As an adult he became increasingly obsessed with creating addictive technology that will allow him to monitor and control the world's data. He also opens the Necropolitan Club.

Creation

Coal was created by Ann Nocenti and Trevor McCarthy. He made his first appearance in Klarion #1.

Major Story Arcs

Klarion

Coal begins plotting to take down the Moody coven, while also introducing his technology. He induces the young Rasp to swallow one of his buddybots, encouraging his paranoia towards his coven members. As the buddybots prove successful, he begins introducing them throughout New York. This attracts the attention of Klarion, who is opposed to the buddybots. He and Klarion fight briefly, before they are interrupted by witch hunters. When Klarion returns from his pocket dimension, Coal fights him again. He attempts to sow doubt and distrust in Klarion's mind, but fails. He is defeated when Klarion absorbs his techno-magic. He survives, though his buddybots have lost public trust.

Powers and Abilities

Coal is partially technology, and has cybernetic enhancements that allow him to interface with the environment. His technology is so far advanced as to resemble magic.

deck: A former warrior of Heven and Angela's best friend.
description:
Angela: Asgard's Assassin

After learning about her true heritage, Angela was renounced by the Angels of Heven. Unwilling to join the Asgardian host, she set out to explore other realms. Upon learning that Odin and Frigga were blessed with another child, Angela returned to Asgardia to visit her family. She stole away the baby girl, and used a magical totem to teleport to another realm. She arrived in Limbo, the realm ruled by the mutant demoness known as Magik, with the Asgardian warriors, including Thor and the Warriors Three, hot on her trail. In Limbo, Sera was waiting for Angela. She'd been preparing another magical totem for their use. Angela handed Sera the baby, and set out to battle the Asgardians. Angela held off all the Asgardians, giving Sera the necessary time to prepare their escape. Once ready, Sera, Angela, and the baby teleported away to another realm: Midgard. They enjoyed a few brief moments of respite (and ice-cream) before the Asgardians were on them once again. The trio teleported away yet again, leaving a frustrated Thor screaming in their absence. They next arrived on Vanaheim, and found themselves in the presence of the Dark Elves. Angela battles the Elves, trying to keep them away from Sera and the baby. When a Dark Elf gets too close, Sera reveals her vast mystical abilities to him, and fends him off. The Dark Elves soon retreat, sensing that the Asgardian host is not far behind. With little time left to spare, Sera leads Angela to the ruins of a temple of love. Deep inside, Angela wades through a pool of molten lava. She is submerged, burned away, and made anew. Because of this, she is able to take with her a special suit made of a metal that protects the wearer from the all-seeing gaze of Heimdall. The suit also grants Angela a set of large wings, much like her Angelic kin.

Powers & Abilities

Sera's origin grants her a degree of enhanced durability, stamina, and invulnerability, as well as super strength. She is a capable fighter, and has proven herself as a master magician.

Origin

Meryet was originally born in ancient Egypt where she tended to the Sphinx just after he received the Ka Stone. The energies from the stone passed to her and she would become immortal through reincarnation. After each death, she was reborn maintaining all her previous memories.

She eventually sought to reunite with the Sphinx and with the power of the Ka Scepter she harnessed the power of the broken Ka Stone. With the power she unknowingly created her own reality where she and the Sphinx were together. She would eventually be defeated by Nova and the New Warriors.

deck: She was the best man for the job.
description:
Origin

Striking terror into the hearts of desperados in the old west The Headless Horseman, a gunslinger seemingly without a head, appeared out of nowhere and dealt justice to those who would rob from the innocent.

Creators

One of the oddest Golden-Age heroines had to be Betty Warren who appeared in only two stories, one in Amazing Mystery Funnies and one in Arrow Comics, both in 1940, as The Headless Horseman a seemingly headless gunslinger to battled bank robbers in the old west.

She pulled this off via a clever disguise that made her seem to be male, taller than her natural height (even without a head) and sans noggin together she and her wonder horse Black Beauty fought your basic western owlhoots and bandits.

In her second story, found in Arrow Comics, she had to deal with the old pulp hero trope of the villain who looks just like hero, or in her case someone who has also figured out the headless getup and started a gang.

Oh yeah, and he also had a condescending dim-bulb sheriff boyfriend.

deck: Extraterrestrial.
description:
Kobeh is an extraterrestrial encountered by Gen 13. Although scant information exists about Kobeh within the pages of Gen 13, the following link has detailed information about Yoda him.

Death

Kobeh's body dematerializes upon his death. Fairchild speculates that this may be how members of his species die. (An equally plausible theory is that this method of death is an effect of Kobeh's membership in a spiritual order and that Kobeh is being reunited with a force of some kind.)

Grunge is visibly distraught at Kobeh's death. Roxy comforts him by telling him that Kobeh is in their hearts; and that as long as they're around, Kobeh will always live on in their memories. It remains unclear how true this is as Kobeh is never mentioned or thought about again by any member of Gen 13.

Speech

Kobeh has taught himself English, although he speaks with a non-standard sentence structure of the form:

<direct/indirect object> <subject> <verb>

For example:

"Merchandise we are."

While under moments of pressure, however, Kobeh tends to revert to the more-standard, subject-first syntax.

"Guards say a monster is loose aboard the ship!" {Emphasis by Kobeh.}

When speaking complex sentences, he mixes both sentence constructions, rendering his meaning difficult to ascertain.

"That spot in the roof, you must break through. Then you must re-enter through the airlock, once you have left this pen." {Emphasis again by Kobeh.}
name: Kobeh
